		<bioghist encodinganalog="545">
			<head>Biographical History</head>
			
		<p>The National Association for Public School Adult Education (NAPSAE) was founded in 1952 to provide 
leadership for the development of adult education in the public schools. Specifically, the organization assisted local adult 
education di-rectors in developing and improving their programs, and encouraged interest in liberal adult education of 
superintendents, school boards, and the public. Its work was handled by the State Projects Committee, headed by an Executive 
Secretary.</p><p>NAPSAE was a department of the National Education Association (NEA) and was affiliated with World 
Confederation of Organizations of the Teaching Profession. Funds were also provided by the Fund for Adult Education and the 
Department of Health, Education, and Welfare.</p><p>Membership in the organization was on an active or associate basis. 
Services varied from consultation with administrators to grants and workshops for establishing, expanding, and improving 
adult education programs. NAPSAE publications include the journals <emph render="italic">Swap Shop for Administrators</emph>, 
published six times yearly; <emph render="italic">Techniques for Teachers of Adults</emph> and 
<emph render="italic">Pulse of Public School Adult Education</emph>, each published eight times yearly; and the annual 
<emph render="italic">Public School Adult Educator's Almanac</emph>, as well as a variety of handbooks, slides, films, 
posters, and folders.</p><p>NAPSAE has since changed its name to the National Association for Public &amp; Continuing Adult 
Education (NAPCAE).</p></bioghist>
		
		<scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
			<head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
			<p>The <emph render="bold">National Association for Public School Adult Education (NAPSAE) Records</emph> 
are divided into three sections: State Projects, Workshops, and Other National Education Association (NEA) Affiliates.   
The collection includes correspondence, printed material such as newspaper and magazine clippings, newsletters, reports, 
programs, budgets, pamphlets, minutes, and questionnaires.  The collection includes material pertaining to the American 
Association of School Administrators, the American Labor Education Service, Robert A. Luke, Elmer A. Mueller, and the 
National Education Association.</p><p>The <emph render="bold">States Projects</emph> section is divided into subsections of 
State Projects Committee and States. Material dealing with the State Projects Committee includes applications for grants, 
minutes of committee meetings, reports on state visits, as well as correspondence. The tentative format of the Project 
Cities Casebook, containing case studies of NAPSAE-grant districts, is also in this section.   The States subsection 
includes material dealing with particular adult education programs and plans in various states and project cities. Most of 
the material is correspondence, but local workshop programs, district studies (notably in Utah and Oklahoma), and newspaper 
and magazine clippings are also filed here.</p><p>The <emph render="bold">Workshops</emph> section contains four folders of 
material concerning Project Directors' workshops and the two-week Community Leadership Laboratory. Tentative and final 
programs, correspondence, pamphlets, memoranda, and reports are included.</p><p>The section of projects by 
<emph render="bold">Other NEA affiliates</emph> includes materials dealing with two educational organizations, the American 
Association of School Administrators (AASA) and the American Labor Education Service (ALES). The AASA materials concern a 
1962 study of numerous foundations and their aid to elementary and secondary public schools and to individual administrators. 
Correspondence in this section is arranged alphabetically. A comprehensive report is also included.</p>

<p>Most of the ALES material is printed material, either publications or mimeographed or dittoed programs on workshops. 
Publications include the annual reports; bulletins; Focus on the United Nations; a report of the international affairs 
pro-gram; a report on New Jersey minority program; and reports on international education and labor exchange. The workshops 
section contains a variety of pamphlets and programs on annual labor education workshops supported or sponsored by the ALES.</p>
		</scopecontent>
		
		<arrangement encodinganalog="351$a">
			<head>Arrangement of the Collection</head>
			<p>The material is 
divided into three series: State Projects, Workshops, and other National Education Association (NEA) Affiliates. Within 
these sections, folders are alphabetically arranged. Correspondence is found in all sections, and in the first two it is 
chronologically arranged. Incoming letters are attached ahead of outgoing letters. </p>
		</arrangement>
		
		<relatedmaterial encodinganalog="544 1">
			<head>Related Material</head>
			<p>The library holds a considerable number of collections related to adult and continuing education. 
 Please refer to &subjindex; for a complete listing of all adult education collections.</p>

<p>In particular, see the records 
of the successor organization, <archref href="../n/napcae.htm">National Association for Public Continuing &amp; Adult Education (NAPCAE)</archref>.  Also, large numbers of NAPSAE's newsletters <emph render="italic">Swap Shop for Administrators</emph>, <emph render="italic">Techniques for Teachers of Adults</emph>, and <emph render="italic">Pulse of Public School Adult Education</emph> may be found in the <extref href="../l/langner_w.htm">William Langner Papers</extref>.</p></relatedmaterial>
		
